<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-136-181 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 959 808</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  June 3 1991 v8 n11 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Study shows power problems changing for better, worse; overalldisturbances down, but power outages up. (National PowerLaboratory five-year study)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dryden, Patrick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Power line disturbances are decreasing but power outages areincreasing in frequency and duration, according to the earlyresults of a five-year site monitoring project presented at ComdexSpring 1991.andP;  The National Power Laboratory (NPL) began the studyin 1990 to organize a database detailing 1,800 monitor months from235 sites in ten US regions.andP;  Comparison of the early results,with 22 percent of the project completed, show the number of powerdisruptions per month declining by 28 percent as voltagefluctuations evened out.andP;  Outages comprise only a tiny portion ofall power problems, and microcomputer and local-area network (LAN)users can expect more of them.andP;  The duration of outages more thandoubled.andP;  Undervoltage disturbances increased 251 percent.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Power FailureStudyTrendsOutlookLocal Area Networks.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>